1
00:00:02,460 --> 00:00:04,905
Foundation Course 1, Talk 3.

2
00:00:05,767 --> 00:00:08,051
The First Noble Truth of Suffering.

3
00:00:08,070 --> 00:00:09,253
The Three Characteristics.

4
00:00:11,477 --> 00:00:14,723
The Buddha taught there were three basic characteristics of our human condition.

5
00:00:15,384 --> 00:00:18,631
Dukkha, often translated as unsatisfactoriness or suffering.

6
00:00:19,452 --> 00:00:21,815
Anicca, impermanence, transiency, change.

7
00:00:22,417 --> 00:00:26,545
And Anatta, no soul, egolessness or insubstantiality.

8
00:00:28,077 --> 00:00:46,119
When he said that our condition was fundamentally unsatisfactory, he meant not only ordinary aches and pains, emotional and personal problems and the sufferings of old age and death, he also meant it in two other respects which are, in fact, the other two characteristics of our existence, transiency and insubstantiality.

9
00:00:48,209 --> 00:00:59,680
The third characteristic of our human condition, anatta, often translated as no soul, but better understood as egolessness or insubstantiality, has to do with how we identify with the wrong things.

10
00:01:00,743 --> 00:01:02,465
We take on a mistaken identity.

11
00:01:03,104 --> 00:01:08,010
We believe ourselves to be the body and mind, the body and the ego or personality.

12
00:01:09,331 --> 00:01:14,858
He divided the human phenomenon into five categories known as khanda or aggregates or less lovingly heaps.

13
00:01:15,832 --> 00:01:19,620
The first heap consists of the material body and how mind experiences this.

14
00:01:20,400 --> 00:01:22,265
The second, all our sensations.

15
00:01:22,965 --> 00:01:24,888
The third, all our perceptions and thinking.

16
00:01:25,570 --> 00:01:31,902
The fourth, all our states of mind, which have been produced by our will and are called volitional conditionings or formations.

17
00:01:32,522 --> 00:01:33,965
They are all our moods and emotions.

18
00:01:34,826 --> 00:01:37,992
The fifth, the knowing of all this, our consciousness.

19
00:01:39,356 --> 00:01:48,748
To understand how this is a mistaken identity it is necessary to investigate the second characteristic of the human condition which is not only applicable to all humans but to the whole of nature.

20
00:01:49,429 --> 00:01:52,492
This is the characteristic of change, anicca.

21
00:01:54,896 --> 00:01:57,358
Built into the idea of change is the concept of time.

22
00:01:58,159 --> 00:02:00,042
It is interesting to see how we use this word.

23
00:02:01,102 --> 00:02:05,128
We say we live in time or we've been through bad times.

24
00:02:05,496 --> 00:02:11,243
The underlying concept is that time is a tunnel or a container within which we live, in which we act out our lives.

25
00:02:12,224 --> 00:02:15,168
Time is somehow separate from us, existing apart from us.

26
00:02:16,169 --> 00:02:20,213
Secondly, we seem to think we have some control over this energy or thing called time.

27
00:02:20,835 --> 00:02:27,301
We often say, I haven't the time, or I lost time, give me time, even I'll make time.

28
00:02:29,492 --> 00:02:41,834
These underlying concepts that time somehow has an independent existence, and that somehow we have some control over it, are what we must investigate to determine the essential quality of change of which time is simply the measure.

29
00:02:45,019 --> 00:02:54,876
One of the rituals in any family gathering is to bring out the photo albums with all the usual comments, delights and laughter, but one of the interesting things is to observe the tense that people talk in.

30
00:02:55,699 --> 00:02:56,961
This is me as a baby.

31
00:02:57,402 --> 00:02:59,325
There I am when I was a teenager.

32
00:02:59,887 --> 00:03:02,110
This is me at your wedding last year.

33
00:03:03,072 --> 00:03:07,838
You can see there's quite a confusion here between the present I am and the past I was.

34
00:03:08,639 --> 00:03:14,188
The identity of this I, with the I of the past and with the I in the present, is confused.

35
00:03:15,531 --> 00:03:23,022
This I, this ego, this personality conceives itself as being the same, whether in the past, present or indeed in the future.

36
00:03:24,370 --> 00:03:27,413
However, the fact is that this is simply not true.

37
00:03:28,336 --> 00:03:30,459
Let us examine the human at the biological level.

38
00:03:31,721 --> 00:03:34,585
The body I had as a baby is simply not the body I have now.

39
00:03:35,485 --> 00:03:38,229
In fact, it is said the body completely changes every seven years.

40
00:03:39,192 --> 00:03:43,358
All that food and drink I have day in and day out go to fuel this process.

41
00:03:43,692 --> 00:03:48,679
Cells duplicate and die, all to an internal pattern, no doubt, a preset blueprint, the DNA.

42
00:03:49,401 --> 00:03:55,229
But nonetheless, the cells are not so much changing as themselves, but dying while other cells take their place.

43
00:03:56,031 --> 00:04:03,140
Even brain cells, which don't actually die, change completely within themselves, so they cannot be called the same cells as the ones we were born with.

44
00:04:05,365 --> 00:04:06,887
This is an important point to grasp.

45
00:04:07,747 --> 00:04:11,674
By change, we don't mean that the same thing is simply changing shape.

46
00:04:12,277 --> 00:04:17,225
A piece of clay can be moulded into a cup and then into a saucer, so that we can say it is the same piece of clay.

47
00:04:18,208 --> 00:04:21,072
But when it comes to the body cells, they reproduce and die.

48
00:04:21,512 --> 00:04:23,315
They are not the same cells changing shape.

49
00:04:24,276 --> 00:04:27,822
This came home very strongly to me when I once went to the optician.

50
00:04:27,904 --> 00:04:29,706
My left eye, it seems, had got a little better.

51
00:04:30,307 --> 00:04:31,168
I was surprised by it.

52
00:04:31,689 --> 00:04:42,365
But the optician told me it was surprising that eyesight remained so static, since the actual cornea, the large lens we look through, changes not once in seven years, nor in a year, nor in a month, but once a week.

53
00:04:43,706 --> 00:04:47,951
Yes, indeed, every week I'm looking at the world through a new cornea, and I didn't know it.

54
00:04:49,334 --> 00:04:53,759
In my blithe ignorance, I thought the body changed all right, but not radically.

55
00:04:54,144 --> 00:04:56,588
Now I come to realise that the change is radical.

56
00:04:57,230 --> 00:05:00,774
The body I have now is simply not the one I had seven years ago.

57
00:05:01,336 --> 00:05:01,675
At all.

58
00:05:02,898 --> 00:05:17,418
In other words, it's the difference between an organisation saying it's going to change the staff, meaning training and redeployment, and another organisation which says it's going to change the staff, meaning it sacks everyone it now employs and takes on a totally new workforce.

59
00:05:19,322 --> 00:05:20,605
Our bodies change radically.

60
00:05:21,105 --> 00:05:22,567
They're changing radically even now.

61
00:05:23,067 --> 00:05:32,778
When we perceive this, when we realize this, this transiency, this changing nature, then we begin to understand why the body cannot be a substantial me, a permanent ego.

62
00:05:34,942 --> 00:05:42,310
The ancient Greeks understood this idea and the philosopher Heraclitus used the image of a river for life.

63
00:05:42,331 --> 00:05:46,596
He said no one steps in the same river twice for it is forever changing.

64
00:05:48,196 --> 00:05:54,345
The Buddha, I'm sure, would have pointed out that no one steps in the same river with the same foot, for that too is ever-changing.

65
00:05:55,887 --> 00:06:03,577
We can't say this is my body, because as soon as I say this is my body and thereby identify with it, define myself by it, it's gone, it's changed.

66
00:06:04,379 --> 00:06:07,262
It's like trying to grasp water, it just flows out of the hand.

67
00:06:08,865 --> 00:06:14,473
Not realising this fact of change causes us to identify with the wrong things, and this in turn is the cause of our suffering.

68
00:06:15,500 --> 00:06:18,622
It never occurs to a young person in any real sense that they're growing old.

69
00:06:19,204 --> 00:06:22,326
The first signs of wrinkles on the face, the first grey hairs are traumas.

70
00:06:23,108 --> 00:06:25,829
I knew I was growing old, but I didn't think it would happen now.

71
00:06:27,771 --> 00:06:32,516
Growing old, losing one's powers, watching the changes on the skin all causes tremendous suffering.

72
00:06:33,137 --> 00:06:43,767
We identify so much with our bodies, desiring them to be as we want them to be, that we are forever compensating for the process of change, of growing old, of decay, even to the point of cosmetic operations.

73
00:06:44,170 --> 00:06:51,420
And death, of course, every time we have a little brush with it, be it a near accident or close shave or death of another, fills us with terror.

74
00:06:52,141 --> 00:06:53,543
Who are we when we have no body?

75
00:06:54,305 --> 00:06:57,230
If I am my body, who am I when it dies?

76
00:06:59,653 --> 00:07:05,201
The same critique can be applied to all the other four khandha, the four categories the Buddha divided the human being into.

77
00:07:06,403 --> 00:07:10,009
If we observe our sensations, we see they're all changing all the time.

78
00:07:10,798 --> 00:07:16,708
They are caused by outside stimuli or stimuli from within the mind itself but everyone is unique, rising and passing away.

79
00:07:17,168 --> 00:07:23,678
Others arise that can be similar but not the same ones since the sensations I felt a moment ago have actually passed away.

80
00:07:25,922 --> 00:07:28,685
To see this more clearly we need to return to the concept of time.

81
00:07:29,487 --> 00:07:30,870
Time itself doesn't exist.

82
00:07:31,630 --> 00:07:35,776
It is just a concept in the mind whereby we order the events that have happened to us

83
00:07:36,584 --> 00:07:38,586
Ten years ago I went to my sister's wedding.

84
00:07:38,886 --> 00:07:40,528
Last year I visited them as usual.

85
00:07:40,848 --> 00:07:42,329
This year I will see them in December.

86
00:07:43,310 --> 00:07:49,336
Although I speak as though all this is real now, in fact nothing's happening at all by way of my sister.

87
00:07:51,298 --> 00:07:52,940
Let's say it's now eight o'clock in the evening.

88
00:07:53,442 --> 00:07:55,142
7.45 has come and gone.

89
00:07:55,624 --> 00:07:56,644
It no longer exists.

90
00:07:57,045 --> 00:07:59,728
In fact, 7.49 has gone, no longer exists.

91
00:07:59,947 --> 00:08:01,649
It has collapsed, disappeared, vanished.

92
00:08:02,011 --> 00:08:03,451
It is no longer.

93
00:08:04,427 --> 00:08:07,514
Now 8.01 has not yet arrived.

94
00:08:07,533 --> 00:08:09,057
It too doesn't exist in any way.

95
00:08:09,798 --> 00:08:17,312
The only existence, the only real point that I experience in which I am actually alive is this now, this very moment, 8 o'clock.

96
00:08:18,954 --> 00:08:21,019
We live on this knife edge of time.

97
00:08:22,012 --> 00:08:26,339
Awareness, what we are developing in meditation, is a faculty that can only exist in the now.

98
00:08:27,182 --> 00:08:28,704
We can't be aware of yesterday.

99
00:08:28,745 --> 00:08:30,507
Awareness doesn't live there.

100
00:08:31,129 --> 00:08:32,371
We can't be aware of tomorrow.

101
00:08:32,511 --> 00:08:33,794
Awareness is not born there.

102
00:08:34,817 --> 00:08:38,123
Awareness arises only here and now in this minute moment.

103
00:08:38,884 --> 00:08:43,192
Awareness and consciousness are simply here and now and at no other time.

104
00:08:45,804 --> 00:08:50,828
The speed of this process, the arising and falling of each and every moment of consciousness is tremendously fast.

105
00:08:51,669 --> 00:09:04,020
Nuclear physicists have timed the existence of matter, subatomic particles of which all our bodies are constituted, as a million, million, million, ten thousandths of a second, or one to the power of twenty-three.

106
00:09:04,981 --> 00:09:06,962
That's a very small moment of existence indeed.

107
00:09:07,724 --> 00:09:14,850
And the Buddha teaches that within that moment of matter existing, seventeen consciousnesses, thought moments, arise.

108
00:09:17,327 --> 00:09:18,528
Let us recap then on time.

109
00:09:18,849 --> 00:09:21,131
First, it doesn't exist by way of extension.

110
00:09:21,231 --> 00:09:22,712
There is no past whatsoever.

111
00:09:22,972 --> 00:09:24,254
It has collapsed into nothingness.

112
00:09:24,835 --> 00:09:25,576
There is no future.

113
00:09:25,596 --> 00:09:26,297
It's not here.

114
00:09:27,037 --> 00:09:29,419
There is only this infinitesimal moment.

115
00:09:30,019 --> 00:09:31,701
This is the only existence we have.

116
00:09:32,442 --> 00:09:37,326
It arises out of nothing, sustains itself for that infinitesimal length of time and then ceases.

117
00:09:38,928 --> 00:09:43,133
When we watch the breath in meditation, we are observing time in a gross way.

118
00:09:44,884 --> 00:09:47,489
The in-breath begins, it is sustained and then ends.

119
00:09:48,311 --> 00:09:49,753
That's it, one in-breath gone.

120
00:09:50,914 --> 00:09:53,139
The out-breath begins, sustains and ends.

121
00:09:53,379 --> 00:09:55,261
That's it, one out-breath gone.

122
00:09:56,543 --> 00:10:01,753
By observing the breath process we are observing, getting to know intimately this passage of moments of time.

123
00:10:02,594 --> 00:10:06,740
Each breath outwardly similar, yet a totally different creation from the last.

124
00:10:07,514 --> 00:10:09,918
We don't live in or through a time object.

125
00:10:10,599 --> 00:10:13,703
Real time is just our actual existence.

126
00:10:13,724 --> 00:10:15,265
This existence is here and now.

127
00:10:15,767 --> 00:10:17,570
We can't lose it or hold on to it.

128
00:10:18,091 --> 00:10:19,072
It can't be repeated.

129
00:10:19,552 --> 00:10:22,236
Each moment of existence is unique and total.

130
00:10:22,658 --> 00:10:24,379
It arises and passes away.

131
00:10:24,880 --> 00:10:30,109
This transiency, this anicca, is a fundamental characteristic of the physical and mental world.

132
00:10:30,910 --> 00:10:34,416
It is a fundamental characteristic of the me, the human being.

133
00:10:37,062 --> 00:10:43,544
Just as this is true of our physical bodies and sensations, so it is also true of the third candor aggregate, our perceptions.

134
00:10:44,149 --> 00:10:45,851
We can only perceive what there is now.

135
00:10:46,613 --> 00:10:50,937
I can only see a cup when a cup is there, and perceptions of the cup arise and pass away.

136
00:10:51,918 --> 00:10:58,426
When these perceptions are purely mental, images, words, ideas, value judgments of good and bad, they also arise and pass away.

137
00:10:59,206 --> 00:11:02,730
And they never arise again, but new ones affected by new information arise.

138
00:11:03,451 --> 00:11:09,177
So our perceptions, our ideas, our thoughts, are always arising and passing away, always changing.

139
00:11:11,504 --> 00:11:19,817
Again, these same arguments pertain to our states of mind, the volitional conditionings, be they moods and emotions of depression, anxiety, anger, or joy, happiness and peace.

140
00:11:20,639 --> 00:11:23,062
Whatever the state of mind, it never repeats itself.

141
00:11:23,884 --> 00:11:25,888
So which state of mind shall I identify with?

142
00:11:26,548 --> 00:11:28,071
Which one shall I call me or mine?

143
00:11:28,832 --> 00:11:34,542
If I define myself in my depression, I'm a depressive, what am I when happiness arises?

144
00:11:35,062 --> 00:11:45,682
If I say I'm all my moods and emotions, then I fall into the error of believing I is existing yesterday when I was depressed, now when I'm angry, and tomorrow when I will be happy.

145
00:11:46,283 --> 00:11:49,048
But this I is only now, and this now passes away.

146
00:11:49,750 --> 00:11:52,975
It is a delusion to identify with the past and the future.

147
00:11:55,419 --> 00:11:58,385
The same with the final candor, or aggregate consciousness.

148
00:11:58,871 --> 00:12:05,440
Often people will argue, oh yes, I agree I'm not my body and other mental factors, since it's all arising and passing away, I see that now.

149
00:12:06,240 --> 00:12:09,585
But my consciousness is steady, I am my consciousness, my knowing of these things.

150
00:12:10,966 --> 00:12:20,457
However, in meditation, this last hold onto our false identity begins to evaporate, for we begin to realize there can only be consciousness when there is an object to be conscious of.

151
00:12:21,350 --> 00:12:28,557
If I were to enter a space with no objects at all, and the mind itself produced no thinking, no images, what would I be conscious of?

152
00:12:29,538 --> 00:12:30,799
Consciousness begs an object.

153
00:12:31,541 --> 00:12:33,842
Without an object there is no consciousness, no knowing.

154
00:12:34,943 --> 00:12:37,667
Indeed there are times when we are unconscious, not conscious.

155
00:12:38,908 --> 00:12:42,011
If I say, I am my consciousness, who am I?

156
00:12:42,471 --> 00:12:47,037
In deep sleep, or anaesthetised on the operating table, or knocked unconscious.

157
00:12:50,392 --> 00:12:55,860
So here we have investigated the first noble truth and the point of view of the three characteristics of existence.

158
00:12:56,621 --> 00:13:04,794
Transiency, anicca, unsatisfactoriness, dukkha, and egolessness or insubstantiality of the personality, anatta.

159
00:13:06,798 --> 00:13:11,504
The Buddha, when he was enlightened, at first thought his discoveries too subtle for people to understand.

160
00:13:12,397 --> 00:13:15,539
but persuaded otherwise, he sought out his five former disciples.

161
00:13:16,140 --> 00:13:22,346
They had left him a while earlier because he ate some milk rice, and they thought he was giving up the training of an ascetic and gone soft.

162
00:13:22,366 --> 00:13:25,669
But in fact, this meal gave him the energy to reach full enlightenment.

163
00:13:27,292 --> 00:13:30,534
When he approached them, they were reluctant at first to receive him.

164
00:13:31,475 --> 00:13:38,623
But as he came closer, his presence was all too powerful, and they prepared a seat for him, and he taught the Dharma by way of the Four Noble Truths.

165
00:13:39,970 --> 00:13:50,525
At the end of this first discourse, known as the turning of the wheel of the law, one of the four, Kondanya, was enlightened, or as the scripture says, the spotless immaculate vision of the Dharma arose in him.

166
00:13:52,469 --> 00:14:01,042
Later that same day, after they had all shared the food brought in from alms round, he gave the second discourse, in which the three characteristics of existence are taught for the first time.

167
00:14:02,504 --> 00:14:03,666
This is how it ends.

168
00:14:04,337 --> 00:14:18,118
When a wise disciple understands that the five aggregates are transitory, unsatisfying and do not constitute a permanent self, non-attachment to the body, sensations, perceptions, emotions and consciousnesses arises.

169
00:14:19,519 --> 00:14:23,525
As non-attachment arises, sense desires and attachments fade away.

170
00:14:24,407 --> 00:14:28,133
With the fading away of sense desires and attachments, the heart is liberated.

171
00:14:29,033 --> 00:14:31,277
With liberation, the knowledge arises.

172
00:14:32,178 --> 00:14:33,179
I am liberated.

173
00:14:35,253 --> 00:14:37,255
This is the fundamental teaching of the Buddha.

174
00:14:37,996 --> 00:14:43,586
Through meditation and throughout our daily life, these characteristics should become more and more plain to us.

175
00:14:44,366 --> 00:14:45,187
Life is changing.

176
00:14:45,649 --> 00:14:48,974
This body, this mind, is not me, not mine.

177
00:14:50,095 --> 00:14:53,780
Identifying with it causes me to have wrong expectations, false hopes.

178
00:14:54,601 --> 00:14:58,067
This wrong identification is the cause of all my suffering.

179
00:14:59,009 --> 00:15:03,014
Not to identify with them is to lose my attachment to them, to be non-attached.

180
00:15:03,703 --> 00:15:11,914
These insights lead us to a proper relationship with ourselves and others, and ultimately leads to the experience which is beyond body and mind, nibbana.

181
00:15:13,496 --> 00:15:20,606
We can say that the experience of nibbana is the discovery of our true identity, and it establishes a new way of relating to ourselves and the world.

182
00:15:21,408 --> 00:15:23,129
What is this new relationship?

183
00:15:23,532 --> 00:15:31,241
It is simply that since everything arises and passes away, I do not regard it as a me or a mine, a soul or self.

184
00:15:31,261 --> 00:15:37,229
I come to realize that when I wrongly identify with all this, it is a cause of suffering.

185
00:15:37,249 --> 00:15:38,250
I become non-attached.

186
00:15:39,052 --> 00:15:42,135
But let me hasten to add that this is not a cold detachment.

187
00:15:42,796 --> 00:15:43,356
Far from it.

188
00:15:43,957 --> 00:15:46,801
Because of this perspective, the heart is liberated.

189
00:15:47,783 --> 00:15:51,226
We begin to find real wisdom and true compassion.

190
00:15:53,889 --> 00:16:08,777
In conclusion then, the more we become aware of the transient changing, radically changing nature of our lives, the more we realize there is no stopping place, no rest, no stability, no security.

191
00:16:10,299 --> 00:16:15,730
The more we accept these facts, the more we live within the flow of living and work within it.

192
00:16:16,942 --> 00:16:32,667
Through meditation, coming to terms with the ever-changing nature of our lives, we free ourselves of false fears and frustrations, fearing the loss of what we cannot actually keep, frustrated by not being able to achieve what is actually unachievable.

193
00:16:34,028 --> 00:16:42,341
It leads to a greater realism, and in that greater realism we will find the peace and joy we all so dearly seek.

194
00:16:44,296 --> 00:16:47,027
Well, I hope you found this talk interesting and helpful.

195
00:16:48,211 --> 00:16:50,100
May all of you be happy and peaceful.

196
00:16:50,783 --> 00:16:53,715
May all of you attain the nirvanic peace within.

